There was no report of impacts to storm drains or water ways. 1640 EST, USES arrived on site. According to the supervisor, the fire department applied absorbent and sweep the material into a pile. About a 25 ft long by 3 ft wide area of concrete was impacted. (2) 55 gallon steel drums of spent absorbent and debris were generated and taken off site for proper disposal.

column168: The shipment arrived leaking. The outer box was soaked & emitting a strong alcohol odor. Upon opening the box we found an opaque in color, plastic, one gallon bottle that was missing its' plastic screw on cap. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response info nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The package & contents were placed in a salvage drum pending an FAA inspection. The drum is in the C-7 Bond Cage.
column169: No comments provided

column168: The shipment was found leaking in the sort. Upon opening the box we found two metal, round, friction lid cans. One can had two loosely attached can clips & the other can only had one clip. As the cans were larger than 250mL, the clips will not meet the 75kPa inner pressure requirement. The can with one clips was the one that spilled. The spill was recovered & the shipment was placed in a salvage drum pending an FAA inspection.

column168: On the morning of 10/9/2019, Veolia employees discovered that a tote of a caustic solution  containing sodium hydroxide was slightly leaking. The tote had shipped from General Electric on  10/02/2019. This morning (10/9/2019), upon arrival at the Veolia 10-day facility in Schenectady, NY, employees observed a leak from a trailer that was parked overnight at the Veolia 10-day transfer  facility. Employees attempted to determine where the tote was leaking as only small drips from the  container were noticed. Employees identified a small cut in the sidewall of a plastic tote and decided to transfer the contents of the tote into another tote.    After transferring the contents of the leaking tote, employees investigated the source of the leaking  tote. A small scrape and cut was visible in the sidewall of the plastic container. It is assumed that a  forklift caused the damage at the original shipper location as the containers were not moved at the  Veolia 10-day transfer facility.    Employees cleaned up the less than 2-gallons of solution in the back of the original transport vehicle as well as a small amount of solution that made it to the ground at the Veolia Schenectady, NY  10 day in-transit facility. The material that was placed into a new tote was sent to Stablex in Canada for appropriate disposal without any further issues. All spill clean up material was also collected and  sent for appropriate waste disposal.
column169: Veolia's best guess as to what happened was that the tote was damaged by the original offeror of  the shipment. Veolia will notify the customer that better care should be used when handling totes and to try and avoid damaging the totes when using a forklift.

column168: On 10/01/2019 at around 1300 hours EST CSXT personnel reported a release from tank car ACFX72446, load Acetone, coming from the top of the car at Chester Yard, Montgomery, AL. The car was isolated and the shipper, Sabic, was notified. MEI, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found a release coming from the manway due to a deteriorated and improperly installed manway gasket. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Sabic (T (713) 978-5567 M (713) 775-4160, E fermin.navarro@sabic.com).  MEI installed a new manway gasket and secured the manway.  The car was released. KENNETH BAREFIELD WAS CONDUCTING A HAZMAT INSPECTION ON A CUT OF CARS THAT WERE RECENTLY DROPPED IN OUR YARD BY THE CSX; HE NOTICED CAR GATX 68654 HAD PINE OIL RESIDUE ON THE LADDER. HE THEN CHECKED THE DOME BOLTS AND NOTICED THEY WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT. KENNETH THEN NOTIFIED THE TRAINMASTER, AND ALE DISPATCHED ITS TANK REPAIR MEN. UPON INVESTIGATION THE REPAIR MEN CONFIRMED THAT ALL DOME BOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT, AND THE GASKET WAS NOT CORRECTLY PLACED BEFORE THE DOME BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED. PER TANK REPAIR MEN, DUE TO THE DOME BOLTS NOT BEEING TOOL TIGHT AND THE PLACEMENT OF THE GASKET, IT CAUSED GATX 68654 TO LEAK IN TRANSIT. ALE TANK REPAIR MEN CORRECTLY PLACED THE GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE DOME BOLTS TOOL TIGHT. GATX 68654 IS SCHEDULED TO BE PLACED IN ALE SHOP AND HAVE THE RESIDUE REMOVED FROM THE TANK CAR.

column168: On October 12, 2019, at 0452, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal LSL regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 55-gallon metal drum of Ethyl Acrylate, 15 ppm MEHQ (Ethyl acrylate, stabilized, UN1917) was punctured, releasing approximately 30 gallons of product on to the trailer floor.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum was containerized in (1) 85-gallon metal drum and all other debris was containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum.  The waste drums were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0810 ET, ERTS was notified by Joseph Caldwell with Roadrunner Transport regarding a Sodium Hydroxide release from (2) 55lb plastic bags that occurred on the dock floor. The initial cause is currently unknown, but bags are reported to have arrived punctured. Environmental Contractor reports 2 bags were damaged. The 1 cup release impacted only the pallet. The damaged bags and sweepings have been containerized into a 55 gallon DF. All waste collected for pending disposal.

I cut open the bottom of the box, opened the folded flaps and found craft paper crumpled up in multiple layers. I peeled back the layers to find one aerosol can that could not be sent as a single package. This was not an overpack, but rather a combination package. I took pics of the shipment and contents and forwarded them to FedEx FAA PHI Steven Redeker. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection.

column168: On 10/10/2019, at 1501 hours, Mobile Repair Unit personnel in the CSXT Niagara Falls Yard discovered UTLX 202638, a residue tank car of Methyl Methacrylate, leaking from the vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and the NRC, NYDEC, NYDOT and shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2019-1010-301). HEPACO, LLC, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief device leaking vapor. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Mario Deviaso of Dupont, phone 716-879-1849. Contractor personnel removed the defective vacuum relief device and replaced with a solid closure plug, thus securing the vapor release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be completed. Cause Code: 674 NARRI: 28
column169: (NAR Cause Code: 674 Vacuum Relief Valve o ring damage)

Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Bruce Melvin 804-541-5431. column168: ON 10/7/2019 AT 13:15 A SEFL DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A PALLET TO SHAKESPEARE. WHEN THE LIFT OPERATOR PICKED UP THE PALLET AND STARTED TO BACK OUT OF THE TRAILER, THE SEFL DRIVER NOTICED A LEAKING PAIL. HE CUT THE SHRINK WRAP AND REMOVED THE PAIL FROM THE PALLET, PLACING IT IN A NEARBY PLASTIC DRUM TO PREVENT MATERIAL FROM LEAKING INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE TOW MOTOR OPERATOR WAS OVERCOME BY THE SMELL AND WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION, SHE WAS NOT ADMITTED BUT TREATED AND RELEASED. THE 5 GALLON BUCKET HAD AN OBVIOUS MARK ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PAIL THAT LOOKED LIKE A BLADE MARK FROM A LIFT, APPROXIMATELY 1 QT WAS LOST FROM THE CONTAINER ONTO THE WOODEN PALLET AND WOODEN TRAILER FLOOR.
column169: WOULD RECOMMEND ADDITION LIFT TRAINING FOR THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR AND INSTRUCT DRIVER TO REMOVE EVERYONE FROM ANY SPILL SITE.

column168: I WAS NOTIFIED AT 10:30 ON 10/13/19 BY OUR SHOP PERSONNEL THAT THEY WERE SMELLING WHAT THEY THOUGHT WAS POSSIBLY A PROPANE OR NATURAL GAS LEAK. column168: Waycross, GA – 10/09/2019 – CPDX 111063 – Liquefied Petroleum Gas     On 10/09/2019 at 2300 railroad hazardous materials contractors discovered residue Liquefied  Petroleum Gas CPDX 111063 with a release at the pressure relief device, while at the CSX Rice Yard in  Waycross, GA.  The car was isolated and NRC notification (report number 1260723) and CHEMTREC  notification (report number 2019-10-09-00327) were completed.  The shipper Sun Gas (Eddy Torra;  305-635-8682) and the car owner Chevron (James Napier; 832-854-5857) were notified.  Hulls  Environmental and Marion Environmental, CSXT emergency response contractors, applied a  midland kit and burned off the residue vapors.  A mobile repair from UTLX replaced the PRD and  the car is awaiting OTMA approval from the FRA.

column168: 10/15/2019, at 10:47 hours, A CSX mechanical employee in the Manville yard discovered the SHPX222895, a residue tank car of UN 1993 Waste Flammable Liquid, having a vapor release from the manway area of the rail car. The rail car was isolated and Systech Environmental Corporation Pam Alford was notified along with CHEMTREC report 2019-1015-00127 NJ State and NRC. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was having a vapor release from the manway area of the rail car. Upon checking the manway gasket. The gasket was found to be improperly installed and cracked. The issue identified where corrected and were communicated to the shipper Pam Alford 419-399-4835 ext 107  Pam.alford.com . Contractor personnel installed new nozzle gasket secured the rail car. The rail car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

On 10/14/2019, ERTS received called from XPO XDE regarding a chemical spill. Caller stated that at 1625 ET, (2) 5 liter plastic jugs containing KATHON™ 886 MW BIOCIDE were damaged after falling off the pallet while offloading onto trailer dock fully releasing product onto dock floor. Caller stated that terminal personnel covered release with saw dust and secured a perimeter around spill site due to the hazardous nature of the product. After reviewing the SDS with the caller it was determined a contractor would need to respond for spill clean up. ERTS contacted Hepaco for dispatch and was given an ETA of 1930 ET. Contractor arrived on-site swept, and put down more absorbents. The contractor then picked up the remaining absorbents and mopped the floor with bleach and sodium bicarbonate. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. All waste was left on-site.

column168: On 10/14/19, At 14:33 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO (UWY) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 1 gallon of UN1263 released from a 55 gallon DM as a result of a forklift puncture. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to clean and manage this release. ERTS notified Talon LPE, the contractor placed damaged drum into a 95 gallon DF over pack for disposal, and added absorbents for precaution. All waste has been left on-site.

On 10/16/2019 ,At 0951 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (XPP) about a cargo release.  It was reported that due to unknown reasons, 15-gal of Hexamethyldisilazane (Hazardous - UN1992) was released from (1) 55 gallon metal drum. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor and asphalt beneath.  The caller is requested a contractor due to the hazardous state and waste amount that is in the trailer and on the asphalt. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. Hexamethyldisilazane contacted the trailer floor it was evaporated by the time the contractors were mitigating the hazard, it does have a vapor pressure of 13.8 mm Hg at 25 deg C (pubchem). Contractors could tell the pallet was impacted. The pallet was cut up and containerized into a 55 DM. The drum was missing ~10-15 gallons. The cause appeared to be from impact with a sharp or protruding object about 2/3 from the bottom of the drum. After applying positive pressure with a intrinsically safe ram fan, contractors then verified the site was clean by utilizing a 5 gas monitor with a Photo Ionizing Detector (Hexamethyldisilazane, IP 8.5) and combustible gas indicator that verified the lower explosive limit to be 0%. The spill is now remediated, and the waste has been varied to be marked correctly and left onsite.

On 10/18/2019, XPO - NPB contacted ERTS regarding a cargo release. Caller reported at 0930 est, (1) 2 gallon poly pail containing CLEARLYTE® STRIPPER 200 (potassium hydroxide) was discovered damaged on trailer 3117440 releasing approximately 1 gallon of product to the trailer floor. Caller reported cause of damaged was due to broken pallet, what looked like a nail puncture possibly. After reviewing the SDS it was determined ERTS would need to contacted a contractor for clean up and containment. The release has been absorbed by the cardboard underneath and the pails need to be containerized. XPO requested a team to respond Monday, 10/21 to containerize the pails. ERTS contacted Alpha-Omega. On 10/21 AOTC arrived on site at 1100 est and located a pallet of 5-gallon jerricans on the dock. The leak was due to a faulty lid/closure that spilled 0.5 gallons of CLEARLYTE® STRIPPER 200 (potassium hydroxide). Vinegar and copious amounts of water were used to decontaminate the salvageable product and the impacted concrete. There was one 55 gallon over pack of waste generated and left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The transferred tote was sent back to terminal XMA and all waste relocated to OS&D.

column168: On 10/24/19, at 0919 ET, XPO Logistics terminal XDP contacted ERTS regarding a cargo release. Caller reported at 0848 est, (1) 100-lb fiberboard drum containing "Super Clean Powder" was torn open while being offloaded on trailer 3178183, releasing approximately 20-lbs of material onto trailer floor. After reviewing the SDS with caller it was determined ERTS needed to send a team out for waste clean up due to the hazardous properties of the material. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to manage the spill. Hepaco confirmed 40-lbs released and affected a 3' X 5' area within the trailer. Hepcao swept the released material into (1) 55 gal fiber over-pack before applying a neutralizing agent to the trailer floor. All waste generated has been left on site with the terminal and staged in OS&D.

column168: On October 24, 2019, at 1245 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal USU regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, (5) 50-pound paper bags of Sodium Carbonate Peroxyhydrate (UN3378) were punctured, releasing approximately 5 pounds of product on to the trailer floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with the proper PPE.  The damaged bags, released product and all other debris were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On October 24, 2019, at 0259 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XMI regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, (1) 5-gallon metal pail of Ethanol Solution (UN1170) was damaged, releasing approximately 1 cup of product on to the dock floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged container, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 10-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

at ~1825 on Thursday, 10/24/2019, while unloading anhydrous ammonia to a supply system, a pinhole leak developed in the 20' transfer hose.  The onsite technicians immediately stopped the transfer and isolated the hose from both the unloading trailer and the supply system.  The release occurred for approximately 5 minutes before the technicians were able to isolate the hose and drain the contents into a water tote to mitigate the release.

On October 28, 2019 at approximately 0015 hours Marcus Fox, CSX Trainmaster reported that in the Hamlet, NC yard, found tank car UTLX 12076 loaded with Sodium Bichromate leaking from the bottom of the tank car. HEPACO a CSXT response contractor responded and found UTLX 12076 leaking from the bottom of the tank car around the bottom outlet valve. The tank car was isolated and the Shipper Elementis Chromium was notified, HEPACO responded and  found that three of the four bolts holding the bottom outlet to the tank car were less than tool tight. HEPACO tightened all four bolts and the bottom outlet valve continued to leak. UTLX 12076 was then transloaded to UTLX 41978. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Elementis Chromium (Rick McBrayer PH# 910-232-0916). UTLX 12076 was cleaned and purged and Elementis Chromium obtained an OTMA-3 to move the tank car to home shop. This did require a special switch.

column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRYING TO OFFLOAD HOT WAX AT THE CONSIGNEE BY SUPPLYING AIR TO THE TRAILER. THE WAX WOULD NOT OFFLOAD SO THE DRIVER DETERMINED THAT THE "CHRISTMAS TREE" FITTING WAS CLOGGED WITH WAX. THE DRIVER WENT TO THE TOP OF THE TANK AND THE PSI GAUGE ON THE FITTING READ 0. SINCE THE FITTING WAS CLOGGED WITH WAX, THE GAUGE WOULD HAVE READ 0 BECAUSE THE AIR COULDN'T FLOW THROUGH THE FITTING. INSTEAD OF "BURPING" THE TANK, THE DRIVER STARTED UNSCREWING THE FITTING WHICH THE PRESSURE ON THE TANK MADE THE FITTING FLY OFF WHICH WAS FOLLOWED BY THE HOT WAX. HOT WAX SHOT IN THE AIR AND LANDED ON THE DRIVERS UPPER BODY. (HEAD, NECK, SHOULDER, ARMS, HANDS.) THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND CLEANUP CREW WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE APPROXIMATE 70 GALLONS OF WAX THAT WAS LEFT ON THE GROUND.
column169: WE WILL ADD MORE TRAINING ON THE HANDLING OF THE FITTING BUT ARE GOING TO GO FOR THE DO NOT REMOVE UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCE APPROACH.

column168: AT 07:45 OF OCTOBER 4, 2019 THE CARDINAL HEALTH (CAH) DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON US ROUTE 1 APPROACHING US ROUTE 72 IN THE MIDDLE OF 3 LANES. THE DRIVER STATED ATTEMPTED CHANGE LANES TO THE RIGHT MOST LANE, WHEN HE STRUCK AN UNOCCUPIED/UNACCOMPANIED BOX TRUCK PARKED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY. THE BOX TRUCK WAS PARKED ON THE SHOULDER WITH ROADSIDE WARNING TRIANGLES. THE CAH DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO AN AREA HOSPITAL WITH MINOR INJURIES.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE DELAWARE STATE POLICE, LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT & THE STATE OF DELWARE - DIVISION OF WASTE AND HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES - EMERGENCY RESPONSE & STRATEGIC SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. US ROUTE 1 WAS CLOSED FROM APPROXIMATELY 08:15 AM WHILE THE VEHICLES WERE REMOVED AND THE DEBRIS WAS CLEARED.  CAH STAFF ARRIVED ON SCENE AND OBSERVED THAT BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS INTACT. PACKAGING WERE INSPECTED AND SURVEYED. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE SHIPMENT CONTAINERS. ALL SURVEYS SHOWED MEASUREMENTS BELOW REGULATORY LIMITS. THE LIMITED QUANTITY PACKAGES WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE SHARON HILL, PA CAH FACILITY. THE AREA AROUND THE CRASH WAS ALSO SURVEYED AND NO CONTAMINATION WAS FOUND. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  THE ROADWAYS WAS RE-OPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15 AM. TOTAL ESTIMATE OF DAMAGES NOT AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT AND WILL BE REPORTED WHEN AVAILABLE. ALL MISSING INFORMATION WILL BE PROVIDED AS IT BECOMES AVAILABLE.
column169: AT THIS TIME, THERE ARE NO RECOMMENDATIONS OR ACTIONS TO BE TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. THE DRIVER WILL CONTINUE TO USE CAUTION WHEN CHANGING LANES AND ALLOW SUFFICIENT DISTANCE BETWEEN  CARS TO ACCOUNT FOR REACTION TIME.  THE BLOCKING, BRACING AND PACKAGING PREVENTED RELEASE OF MATERIAL AS INTENDED.

column168: ON OCTOBER 2, 2019 LAWRENCE LIVERMORE NATIONAL LABORATORY (LLNL) DISCOVERED THAT A 2000 GALLON DOT 406 TANKER TRUCK CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 1800 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SENT OFF-SITE FOR VEHICLE MAINTENANCE WITHOUT SHIPPING PAPER, APPROPRIATE PLACE CARDING, AND THAT THE TANK WAS OUT OF COMPLIANCE WITH 49 CFR 180.401 REQUIREMENTS FOR THE CONTINUING QUALIFICATION, MAINTENANCE OR PERIODIC TESTING OF A CARGO TANK. UPON DISCOVERY OF THIS ISSUE LLNL ARRANGED FOR THE TANKER TO BE EMPTIED OF FUEL BY A FULLY QUALIFIED VENDOR, AND THE TANK WAS PURGED OF VAPORS USING DRY ICE TO REMOVE ANY POTENTIAL CLASS 3 HAZARD. ALL THE HAZARD WARNINGS, LABELS PLACE CARDS ETC. WERE SECURELY COVERED TO ALLOW TRANSPORTATION OF THE TANKER BACK TO THE LLNL SITE.
column169: THE TANKER IS TYPICALLY ONLY USED ON THE LLNL SITE WHICH IS A SQUARE MILE SITE SURROUNDED BY FENCES AND GUARDS WITH NO PUBLIC ACCESS THAT ALLOWS THE TANKER TO BE USED WITHOUT FOLLOWING DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS. SPECIFIC PROCEDURES AND TRAINING WILL BE DEVELOPED TO ENSURE LLNL PERSONNEL INVOLVED WITH THE FUEL TANKER ARE FULLY AWARE OF THE APPLICABLE REGULATIONS AND RESPONSIBILITIES WHEN TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OVER PUBLIC ROADS.

column168: RECEIVED A CALL FOR A HAZARDOUS LEAKER. WENT LOCATION OF SPILL. FOUND PACKAGE WITH WET CORNER. RETURNED TO DMP AREA TO PROCESS LEAKER.

PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DMP BY THE RESPONDER FROM THE OUTBOUND WALL PD-1. IN THE DMP PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN 6, ONE GALLON METAL CANS OF SUNNYSIDE DENATURED ALCOHOL, BEING SHIPPED AS A FLAMMABLE HAZ-MAT. THIS PACKAGE HAD AT SOME POINT BEEN DROPPED OR CRUSHED CAUSING ALL THE INNER METAL CANS TO BE DENTED AND DAMAGED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CANS. THE BOTTOM SEAM ON ONE OF THE CANS WAS SPLIT ALLOWING A PORTION OF THE ALCOHOL TO LEAK AND STAIN THE OUTER CARTON. ALL PRODUCT WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP AND DISPOSED OF.
PACKAGE FOUND ALREADY LEAKED EMPTY, HOLE IN ONE CONTAINER
PACKAGE WAS LOCATED IN THE TRAILER NEAR THE WALL. IT HAD LEAKED TOWARDS THE WALL BUT WAS PREVENTED FROM SPREADING. FOLLOWED PROCEDURE AND FOUND THAT 3 OF 4 OF THE CONTAINERS HAD THEIR CAPS OFF.
THE RESPONDER WENT TO THE SPILL AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column168: On 10/28/2019, at 1933 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg discovered GATX 201122, a loaded tank car of Isoprene, leaking from protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, local fire department, West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection, National Response Center, and Federal Railroad Administration were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2019-1029-000010). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release emanating from the magnetic gauging device. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ms. Gerry Sage, phone 904-349-1180. Contractor personnel installed Midland Emergency Response Capping Kit to secure the vapor release. The contents of GATX 201122 were transferred, and the car was cleaned and purged on 11/1/2019. . This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be completed by the CSX Hazardous Materials Team. Cause Code: 479 NARRI: 40

column168: Driver Rafael Resto was on route on Carr#137 in the jurisdiction of Morovis, PR. in a Tank Truck with a capacity of 6,000 gallon: 1,000 of regular gasoline and 5,000 gallon of premium gasoline. Driver was moving at 32 MPH behind  another heavy vehicle.  The preceding vehicle reduced speed to make a right turn. Driver Rafael Resto reduced speed to 11 MPH and moved towards the left lane.  A vehicle described as a white  Hyundai Tucson enters the intersection in an abrupt way and when the Hyundai driver, (50  year old woman with two minor passengers)  saw the tank truck, she suddenly stopped her vehicle. As Mr. Resto hit the brakes and tries to avoid the impact to the Hyundai, the tank displaced to the right and overturned. In the impact, the tank pulled the Hyundai to the road fence at the contrary lane and it was stuck between the truck and the road fence. The Driver suffered no injuries. The Hyundai driver and the accompanying minors were unharmed. The Tank Truck and the Hyundai vehicle suffered major damages. The tank was removed with a specialized tow system and the contents of the tank was transferred to another tank truck.  Spill was treated by specialized environmental workers. Traffic was reopened by 4:00 PM.
column169: While the main cause for the accident was the sudden entering of a vehicle into the intersection, it was not possible for the driver to spot the vehicle and avoid the accident due to the fact that the preceding vehicle blocked his view. To try to avoid this kind of situations, we will remind the drivers of the unexpected incidents that can get into their routes. We will stress the need to be very attentive to the road at all times, especially at night and dawn hours. We will reinforce the need to think in a proactive way, trying to visualize "what can happen" and avoid any distractions while driving.

The Manager on Duty was notified by the ramp agent and the package was removed from further transport.  The item is prohibited from being accepted and transported on HAL.  This item is also prohibited in international mail due to the lithium mark being present. The root cause of the incident resulted from the package not being properly screened and segregated at USPS prior to receipt by HA.

On 10/28/2019, at 1727 hours, an FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector notified CSXT that inside the CSXT Grafton Yard discovered UTLX 201450, a loaded tank car of Fuel Oil, leaking from the Vacuum Relief Device. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a liquid release of lading from the vacuum relief device. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to CSX Transportation Fuel Procurement Personnel. Contractor personnel removed the defective vacuum relief device and installed a closure plug to secure the release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 has been completed.  Cause Code: 466 NARRI: 24

column168: On October 15, 2019 at 1400 ET, ESTES experienced a 7 - gallon release of UN3289, Toxic liquid, corrosive, inorganic, n.o.s., 6.1(8), PGI from one (1) 7 - gallon poly jug due to being punctured by a sharp object while unloading. It was advised that approximately 7 - gallons of product impacted a 5' by 5' area of the trailer floor as well as a 5' by 8' area of the dock floor. Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) dispatched Environmental Services Inc out of South Windsor, CT to the terminal to perform cleanup activities. At 1654 ET, the contractor arrived onsite and neutralized the impacted areas with simple green and then applied granular absorbents to the impacted areas to absorb and solidify the released product. The compromised jug was over packed into one (1) 30 - gallon x - rated poly drum. The spent absorbents and debris were recovered into one (1) 55 - gallon poly drum which was over packed into one (1) 85 - gallon x - rated poly over pack drum. The contractor utilized a drager to pump out the air inside of the trailer to successfully decontaminate the trailer being a confined space. At 1934 ET, Environmental Services Inc confirmed that cleanup was complete and the waste waste staged onsite at the terminal to be managed by terminal personnel. The contractor then departed the site.

column168: JBHU 250498 was found leaking a black tar like substance, seeping through the rear doors of the unit. This shipment is billed as carrying multiple types of hazardous materials inside of the subject container. Customer was contacted, who then dispatched Patriot Environmental Services to assess and to remediate the reported leaking substance. Interior inspection revealed mixed palletized freight varying in sizes and weights loaded throughout the container. There was no lateral \ doorway securement used to secure this shipment, as required by the BNSF Intermodal Rules and Policies Guide. One pallet was found fallen over on its side, the pallet contained "Cromax Premier LE," a paint product registered as a flammable hazardous material UN1263. Due to improper stacking and the lack of cargo securement, the damaged pallet spilled approximately one gallon of product on the container floor.
column169: Shipper must ensure tat proper blocking and bracing is done to prevent load shift and future releases of hazardous materials.

column14: MN 95 WEST OF BENTON CITY RD 7
column168: ON OCTOBER 24, 2019, CENTRA SOTA WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF VAPAM HL (3200 GALLONS, CONTAINED IN (2) 1600 GALLON POLY TANKS, MOUNTED ON A TRUCK) FROM OUR PLANT TO THE APPLICATOR IN A FARM FIELD. WHILE IN TRANSIT, THE DRIVER BECAME AWARE OF A LEAK. THE LEAK BEGAN ON MN HWY 95 JUST WEST OF BENTON CTY 6. THE DIRVER TURNED AROUND AT THE NEXT CROSSROAD, 145TH, AND RETURNED TO THE PLANT ABOUT 6 MILES AWAY VIA MN HWY 95, BENTON CTY 7 AND SHERBURNE CTY 11. LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ROUGHLY 1000 GALLONS OVER AN 8-10 MINUTE PERIOD WHILE DRIVING BACK TO THE PLANT. ONCE BACK AT THE PLANT, THE REMAINDER OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED. THERE IS NO TEXT BOOK RESPONSE FOR EVERY INCIDENT, BUT IN THIS CASE, BY RETURNING TO THE PLANT, WE WERE ABLE TO MITIGATE A TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT AS WELL AS PREVENT AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP HAD WE STOPPED ON THE HIGHWAY OR IN AN UNFAMILIAR FARM FIELD.  THE MN DUTY OFFICER WAS CONTACTED TO REPORT THE RELEASE. I WAS NOT GIVEN A FILE NUMBER BEFORE  BEING TRANSFERRED TO PAT KELLY AT THE MN DEPT. OF AGRICULTURE TO DISCUSS THE SITUATION. ADDITIONALLY, RALPH FREDERICK, SALES REPRESENTATIVE FOR AMVAC, THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT, WAS CALLED FOR GUIDANCE AS WAS BAY WEST ENVIRONMENTAL. ON THE MORNING OF OCTOBER 25, AFTER DOING AN ON AIR MONITOR TEST IN ONE AREA OF THE LEAK ALONG THE ROAD AND DISCUSSION BETWEEN AL PARTIES INVOLVED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SINCE THE PRODUCT HAD EVAPORATED AND/OR DRIED, THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL CLEANUP POSSIBLE OR SUGGESTED.  THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS DUE TO TANK FAILURE FOR REASONS UNKNOWN. THE POINT OF RELEASE WAS THROUGH A CRACK OR SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. I CANNOT SPEAK TO THE AGE OF THE TANK, BUT VISUALLY IT LOOKED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION, NOT SUN FADED OR DAMAGED IN ANY WAY AND WAS MOUNTED SECURELY TO THE VEHICLE.
column169: IN THE FUTURE, WE WILL TALK WITH TANK MANUFACTURERS TO DETERMINE IF THERE IS A STANDARD YEARS OF SERVICE WE SHOULD EXPECT FROM OUR TANKS. WE WILL ALSO CONSIDER UPGRADING THE TANKS USED FOR TRANSPORT OF THESE MATERIALS TO STAINLESS STEEL OR ANOTHER MORE DURABLE PRODUCT.

The employee started attempting to contain the spill and called into the dispatcher and Safety Director.

column168: at approx 13:00 ERTS was contacted by Kyle Goodwin on behalf of Dupre Logistics in regards to a tanker release. According to Kyle about 30 gallons of UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide released from a tanker during a hardware transfer. This release has impacted several drains, and went down to a creek about 1/2 mile. ERTS has secured Lone Star Hazmat to respond and manage this release. 2107 ET, Kyle from Dupre Logistics advised that the owner from Petra estimated approximately 900 gallons to have released and has dispatched Tas Environmental to assist with the cleanup. Lonestar confirmed TAS arrived on site and walked the site along with them and the Municipal Water District. TAS Environmental will be using the vac truck that Lonestar rented from them to recover the rest of the liquid with the frac tank they brought on site.   Petra Chemical has accepted responsibility for the release, clean up and disposal of the waste For waste disposition and/or an additional follow up please contact Dave Byrd. His email is dbyrd@petrachem.com and phone number is 214-352-1900

column168: During loading of a bulk bleach tanker trailer, a PVC pipe elbow broke resulting in bleach spraying in the vicinity.  The pipe fitting failure happened on the transfer pipe between an above ground storage tank and the tanker trailer.  No product made it to the tanker trailer.  Upon discovery, Operations EEs notified Branch Management and started clean up activities.  Most of the bleach was released into the containment dike around the loading area.  However, approximately <= 100 gallons was released onto nearby grass and gravel areas. No EEs were exposed to the bleach and no evacuations occurred.  Total amount released was 1800 gallons. Release was called into NRC pursuant to CERCLA Reporting Quantity being exceeded. Ohio EPA was notified under Storm water permit due to NRC notification.
column169: New loading procedures were implemented for the operator to walk outside after starting the product transfer.  In addition, we are investigating use of a variable speed pump to avoid an hydraulic hammer effect when the transfer is started.

column168: The affected employee was trans-loading Waste Sodium Hydroxide Solution from a barge into a cargo tank. According to our internal incident report the employee stopped the loading process due to a kink in the hose. While he was in the process of reconnecting the hose, the pump was turned on ahead of time by the customer representative. The material from the hose splashed the employee's face, left shoulder/arm and both thighs.   The employee was treated on-site with water and vinegar and a safety shower for approximately 20 minutes. Afterwards, he was taken directly to the emergency room to be evaluated by a physician, the employee was not admitted to the hospital.   The customer has removed any contaminated soil for disposal.
column169: We have worked with our customer to ensure safety rules and site specific hazard training/orientation is provided to all drivers arriving on-site. We also requested the customer to have extra face shields, goggles and aprons on-site and that signage saying "Drivers not allowed to handle hoses during transfers" be put up.   Training has been given to employees to ensure proper PPE is worn, stop work authority and the danger of complacency was discussed. Additional training will be given on hazard identification and recognition. Incident lessons learned notification was sent out to other locations so they are aware of what happened and can reinforce safety principles with employees.

column168: Delivery driver arrived at wrong address and proceeded to unload 275 gallons of heating oil directly into an existing (now abandoned) fill pipe installed through the foundation wall. The driver did not realize the above ground oil tank had been removed from inside the basement and the house (subsequently) converted from oil heat to heat pump. Upon discovery of the mistake, it was evident that product had spread into entire basement and out of basement roll-up door, down driveway, and into the alley way. Driver realized problem and called manager to notify of mistake. Fire Department was already there when manager arrived.  QOC representative immediately made contact with Fire Department and Emergency Management who had already contained situation. The release occurred and initial emergency response occurred between 1710 and 1750. Emergency Management confirmed that product was contained and confined to basement, driveway (76’ from house to end of driveway) and alleyway/easement in back of house (76’ from driveway to immediate right turn out of driveway and into the alleyway). QOC, Progress Environmental, Adam Stewart, City Council, NCDENR all in agreement on actions for remediation. Progress Environmental is managing the final soil testing, remediation, and reporting.
column169: In this case, the driver correctly followed loading and delivery procedures, except checking air flow at vent during delivery. Future training will include even more emphasis on this step in the delivery process. The other contributing factor was the driver's use of personal phone GPS to plan the trip versus the company tablet-based routing system. So, the training process going forward will stress the importance of using the company-provided routing system and increased attention to address verification upon arrival.

column168: ON 10/08/2019 AT APPROXIMATELY 0120 HOURS, HAZMAT TANK CAR TILX 304358 WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) SHREVEPORT, LA RAIL YARD. THE LEAK WAS REPORTED BY KCS YARD PERSONNEL. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND MITIGATE THE LEAK.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND TILX 304358 LEAKING FROM B-END LIQUID VALVE. THE B-END LIQUID VALVE WAS FOUND SLIGHTLY OPEN AND SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG WAS FOUR TURNS LOOSE. THE B-END VAPOR VALVE SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. ADDITIONALLY, THE A-END LIQUID VALVE AND A-END VAPOR VALVE WERE FOUND TO BE SLIGHTLY OPEN. FURTHER, THE A-END VAPOR VALVE SECONDARY PLUG WAS DISCOVERED TWO TURNS LOOSE. ALL CLOSURES WERE SECURED TOOL TIGHT. AFTER SECURING THE CLOSURES, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ALLOWED TIME FOR VENTILATION, AND THEN VERIFIED THAT CLOSURES WERE NOT LEAKING BY APPLYING A SNOOP SOLUTION AND USING AN AIR MONITORING DEVICE. IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED. ESTIMATED RELEASE IS 2 GALLONS. ONCE TILX 304358 WAS VERIFIED SECURE, IT WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: UPON WALK AROUND INSPECTION AT TRUCK STOP, DRIVER NOTICED MATERIAL ON THE LIP OF TRAILER DOOR. WHEN HE OPENED THE DOORS, MATERIAL WAS ON FLOOR OF TRAILER EXTENDING TO THE END GATE. HE COULD NOT ASCERTAIN WHERE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. ABSORBENT SOCKS WERE IN PLACE AT THE END GATE, AS IS STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE FOR HAZMAT'S DRIVERS, WHICH HAD BECOME SATURATED. MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM END GATE ONTO THE LIP OF DOOR. DRIVER THOUGHT THE LEAK WAS MOTION RELATED AS NO MORE MATERIAL HAD ACCUMULATED WHILE SITTING OVER AN HOUR AND THROUGH THE NIGHT. DIRECTION FROM GENERATOR, 3M SITE PERSONNEL WAS TO WAIT UNTIL THE MORNING TO MAKE DECISION AS THE MANAGEMENT STAFF HAD LEFT FOR THE DAY. DELIVERY DESTINATION IS 3M COTTAGE GROVE, APPROX. 400 MILES.  HAZ-MAT ONE WAS CALLED, WHO CONTRACTED ENVIROSERVE TO GO TO TRUCK STOP WITH MONITORS TO DETECT WHAT MATERIAL WAS ON FLOOR. HEPTANE WAS DETECTED. THEY WENT BACK TO THEIR OFFICE (90 MIN. AWAY) TO GET THE REQUIRED UN SPEC DRUM TO PUMP OUT LEAKING DRUM INTO, A PUMP AND SALVAGE DRUM TO PUT THE EMPTIED DAMAGED DRUM INTO. SMALL PIN HOLE IN DRUM WAS DISCOVERED TOWARDS BOTTOM SEAM OF THE LEAKING DRUM WHICH WAS LOCATED INT HE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. TRANSFER WAS MADE INSIDE THE TRAILER, WHICH WAS SUCCESSFUL, AND TRAILER FLOOR AND LIP DOOR WERE WIPED CLEANED.  NO MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.
column169: THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS LEFT ON TRAILER FOR THE TSDF - 3M, COTTAGE GROVE, TO EXAMINE TO DETERMINE WHAT MIGHT HAVE CAUSED THE PIN HOLE IN THE DRUM. APPROPRIATE ACTION TO PREVENT A FUTURE INCIDENT WILL BE TAKEN IF WARRANTED.  AFTER TRAILER WAS UNLOADED, THE END GATE WAS INSPECTED AT REPAIR SHOP IN THE AREA: - NEW SEAL WAS INSTALLED - SMALL AMT. OF RUST WAS CLEANED OUT OF THE TRACK - BOTTOM OF END GATE WAS CLEANED - NO GAPS WERE DETECTED AND GATE WAS NOT FOUND TO BE BENT OR WARPED

column168: The Driver was making a delivery of hydrochloric acid to a pool located at 10 Surfsuide Dr, Tofte, MN.  Driver did not verify the tank he was pumping into and assumed incorrectly that the acid tank was the tank on the right.  The tank on the right was a bleach tank (sodium hypochlorite).  The driver pumped the acid from his truck into the bleach tank causing an off gas of chlorine gas.  The gas was sucked into the neighboring building by an air intake that was located approximately 10ft from the tanks.  A strong odor was noticed in the neighboring building around 5pm.  At this time the building was evacuated and 911 was called.   Tofte FD was onsite at 5:17pm.  Tank was done off gasing.  Full fire crew was onsite at approximately 5:45pm and the building was reoccupied and aired out.    A person was transported by ambulance to the hospital in Grand Marais, MN due to exhibiting possible signs of a chlorine exposure.  The persons actual health and whether they were admitted is unknown.   Fire left around 6:30pm.  Tank was pumped out and system purged with the aid of another employee.  All employees left around 9:30pm.
column169: We are going to be improving labeling of our customers tanks.  This tank had a EPA issued pesticide label that was obscured by the structure containing the tank.  We are going to be adding some kind of labeling to the top of the tank.

column168: THE WASTE ARRIVED AT INGENIUM'S EXEMPT 10 DAY TRANSFER STATION ON 10/28/2019. MANIFEST # 000285480 DAT  A FORKLIFT AND A DRUM GRABBER ATTACHMENT WERE USED TO MOVE A WASTE PAINT DRUM FROM ONE TRUCK TO ANOTHER TRUCK WHERE THE WASTE WAS STAGED ON A VEHICLE AWAITING AN OUTBOUND LOAD TO THE TSDF. NO ISSUE WAS FOUND WITH EITHER PIECE OF EQUIPMENT DURING DAILY INSPECTION.  THE FOLLOWING DAY, AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED A SMALL RED GLOB OF PAINT BELOW THE LOADING DOCK. THE INCIDENTAL SPILL (2 LITERS) WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED AND THE COMPROMISED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SUBSEQUENT TRANSFER TO TSDF  A SINGLE DRUM IN THE OUTBOUND STAGED AREA WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE SOURCE. A SMALL 1/4 INCH WIDE HOLE WAS FOUND, JUST BELOW THE 3RD LOWER CHINE OF ONE UN RATED DRUM. THE DRUM APPEARED TO BE HAVE PUNCTURED BY THE TANG OF ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM GRABBLER. THE DRUM SHOWED EVIDENCE OF THE SCRAPING ALONG THE DRUM LEADING TO THE PUNCTURE POINT. UPON INSPECTION OF THE ATTACHMENT, RESIDUE WAS FOUND ON THE DRUM GRABBER CONSISTENT WITH THE CONTACT POINTS.

column168: On October 30, 2019 at 1550 ET, Stericyle Specialty Waste Solutions experienced a 4 - gallon release of UN1789, Hydrochloric acid, 8, PGII WASTE, from one (1) 5 - gallon jerrican due to being dropped while being unloaded at the dock of thier facility in Piscataway, NJ. At 1555 ET, Stericycle retained Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage and oversee the referenced incident. At 1706 ET, ERTS notified the New Jersey DEP. Operator 86 received the call and issued reference number 191030162957. ERTS then retained First Call Environmental out of Woodbridge, NJ to mobilize to the site to perform cleanup operations. At 1715 ET, the contractor arrived onsite and neutralized the impacted area with soda ash and applied granular absorbents to the impacted area of asphalt parking lot and concrete loading dock. First Call Environmental personnel over packed the compromised jerrican into one (1) 55 - gallon poly drum. The spent absorbents and neutralizer were placed into one additional 55 - gallon poly drum. The contractor staged the waste onsite at the terminal to be managed by Stericycle personnel. At 2000 ET, ERTS notified the National Response Center (NRC) of the release due to being a hazardous waste release. Operator Rawls received the call and issued reference number 1262691.

column168: The transport was heading South on RT 35 loaded with Ethanol when a car was attempting to cross over the RT 35 south bound lanes to access the RT 35 north bound lanes from the RT 32 East bound off ramp. column168: Our driver was unable to slow down or stop as he approached stopped traffic.  To avoid a potential collision, he initiated a turn onto a side road at a speed that caused the truck to overturn. Compressed gas cylinders, liquid gas cylinders, and propane gas cylinders were ejected from the secured load on the truck.  There was no uncontrolled release of product.  The liquid nitrogen cylinders vented safely through a pressure relief valve as it is designed and authorized to do.  No cylinders or cylinder valves failed or released product.  We inspected all cylinders involved in the accident when they were brought to our filling facility. We are filing this report as a response to the request we received dated December 6, 2019 and in response to NRC report No 1262164.

column168: TAYLOR OIL CO., INC. CARRIER WAS STOPPED AT RR CROSSING ON MEMORIAL DRIVE WITH FLASHERS ON. DODGE RAM REAR ENDED CARRIER. DODGE RAM FRONT BUMPER KNOCKED OFF CARRIER'S BUMPER AND PUNCTURED LIQUID VALVE CAUSING DYED DIESEL TO LEAK FROM COMPARTMENT. BOTH VEHICLES WERE REMOVED FROM INTERSECTION OF RR AND LOCATED ON THE WEST SHOULDER OF MEMORIAL DRIVE. ESTIMATED DURATION OF RELEASE WAS 10-15 MINUTES. EMERGENCY SERVICES AND TAYLOR OIL PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT SITE. ONCE EMERGENCY SERVICES GAVE PERMISSION, TAYLOR OIL CO. PERSONNEL DEPLOYED AN ABSORBENT BOOM, REMOVED AND CAPPED DAMAGED LIQUID VALVE. THE BALANCE OF PRODUCT WAS THEN PUMPED OUT TO ANOTHER CARRIER TANK TRUCK. ACT ENVIRONMENT & INFRASTRUCTURE, BARTOW, FL RESPONDED FOR SPILL CLEAN-UP. SEE ATTACHED FLORIDA TRAFFIC CRASH REPORT # 89095059-01. DRIVER OF V1 STATED HE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON MEMORIAL DR. BEHIND V2. DRIVER OF V2 BEGAN TO SLOW DOWN AND EVENTUALLY STOPPED AT THE RAILROAD CROSSING. DRIVER OF V1 STATED HE COULD NOT STOP IN TIME AND STRUCK THE REAR OF V2. DRIVER OF V2 STATED HE WAS STOPPED AT THE RAILROAD CROSSING ON MEMORIAL DR. DUE TO HIM HAULING A PLACARDED MATERIAL. DRIVER OF V2 STATED WHILE STOPPED HE WAS STRUCK IN THE REAR BY V1. NO INJURIES REPORTED ON SCENE. BOTH VEHICLES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE BY BOTH DRIVERS. V2 HAD TO OFFLOAD THE REMAINING FUEL. V2 LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS OF FUEL ONTO THE ROADWAY AND SHOULDER. HIGHLANDS COUNTY ROAD AND BRIDGE RESPONDED AND ASSISTED WITH THE CLEANUP. DRIVER OF V1 AT FAULT FOR CARELESS DRIVING, CITATION NUMBERA49NUJE WAS ISSUED.

column168: THE TRUCKLOAD TRANSFER FROM A FERRIC CHLORIDE RAILCAR WAS IN PROGRESS AND CLOSE TO TARGET WEIGHT. OPERATIONS LOADER SHUT THE AIR VALVE ON THE CAR AND CLIMBED ON THE MANWAY TO DISCONNECT THE AIRLINE. BEFORE HE COULD, THE PRODUCT SIDE FITTING BROKE OFF THE CAR, ALLOWING THE MATERIAL IN THE CAR TO BLOW OUT. SINCE THE AIR VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE ONLY WAY THE CAR COULD RELIEVE PRESSURE WAS THROUGH THE STANDPIPE. IT WAS NOT SAFE TO GO UP AND OPEN IT. IT TOOK ABOUT 50 MINUTES FOR THE RAILCAR TO EMPTY. THE AREA WHERE THE SPILL IS NATURALLY CONTAINED DUE TO SLOPING TERRAIN ON 3 SIDES AND A WALL ON THE 4TH. THIS KEPT THE SPILL IN THE AREA. RESPONSE STARTED AS SOON AS WE COULD ACCESS THE AREA, AND ALL FREE STANDING MATERIAL WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE AREA. IT WAS COVERED IN BETWEEN WORK PERIODS TO PREVENT RAIN OR WEATHER FROM SPREADING IT MORE. AFTER THE RELEASE ENDED AND WE LOOKED AT THE FAILURE, WE FOUND THAT THE THREADED UNLOADING ASSEMBLY HAD PULLED APART AT THE FLANGE CONNECTION. SEE PHOTOS ON SEPARATE DOCUMENT.
column169: IMPLEMENT NEW SALCO UNLOADING ASSEMBLY FOR USE IN UNLOADING FERRIC CHLORIDE RAILCARS. THIS IS A HAZARDSOLVE HEAVY DUTY UHMWPE FITTING OF FLANGED CONSTRUCTION; ELIMINATING THREADED CONNECTIONS. THE MODEL NUMBER IS HSCSLSHMULA23.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSFERRING 4,986 GALLONS OF PURE METHANOL FROM A ISO TANKER TO A TRANSPORT TANKER. EMPLOYEE CONNECTED HOSES AND TURNED ON PUMP TO START THE TRANSFER. EMPLOYEE THEN GOT INTO HIS TRUCK NOT REALIZING THAT PRODUCT BEGAN PUMPING ONTO THE GROUND DUE TO IMPROPER HOSE HOOKUP. ONCE EMPLOYER FAILED TO MAKE PROPER NOTIFICATION PER COMPANY POLICY. THE FOLLOWING DAY COMPANY MANAGEMENT WAS MADE AWARE OF THE RELEASE AND IMMEDIATELY INITIATED AN INVESTIGATION AND REGULATORY NOTIFICATION.  THE INITIAL REPORT WAS THAT APPROXIMATELY 1,100 GALLONS OF METHANOL HAD BEEN RELEASED. THE AREA MANAGER INVESTIGATED THE LEVEL IN THE TANKS AND STRAPPED THE TANKS TO TRY TO DETERMINE ACTUAL AMOUNT RELEASED. THE DETERMINATION WAS THAT APPROXIMATELY 228 GALLONS OF METHANOL WAS THE ACTUAL AMOUNT RELEASED ON THE GROUND. THE RELEASE REMAINED ON SITE, WITH NO OFF SITE IMPACTS. SAMPLES WERE TAKEN TO VERIFY THAT THE SITE WAS CLEAN, OR IF CLEANUP WAS WARRANTED BY BOTH CLARIANT AND THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (TCEQ). ANALYTICAL SAMPLES WERE VERIFIED BY BOTH ENTITIES TO BE NON-DETECT LEVELS AND THUS NO REMEDIATION WAS REQUIRED NOR TAKEN.
column169: POLICY REQUIRES EMPLOYEES TO REMAIN AT TRUCK PUMP CONTROLS DURING PRODUCT TRANSFER. EMPLOYEES WERE PROVIDED WITH A REVIEW OF THE POLICY TO REMAIN AT PUMP CONTROLS WHILE PUMPING TO VERIFY THAT NO LEAKS ARE OCCURRING AND PROPER HOOKUP WAS MADE, AND REPORTING INCIDENTS IMMEDIATELY. BASED ON THE INVESTIGATION, DISCIPLINARY ACTION OF THE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED WAS WARRANTED AND TAKEN.

column162: ATTORNEY FOR DUNCAN OIL TRANSPORTATION SOL.
column168: JEFF MILLERS ACCIDENT REPORT,  JEFF REPORTED TO ME, THAT ON SUNDAY MORNING AROUND 0345 HE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON STATE ROUTE 42 BETWEEN LEBANON AND WAYNESVILLE COMING FROM COVINGTON MARATHON. HE LOADED 6000 GALLONS OF REGULAR FUEL GOING TO PAT PLACE SUNOCO IN WAYNESVILLE. AT 0251 AM JEFF LEFT COVINGTON MARATHON AT 03:52 HE TRAVELED NORTH THROUGH LOVELAND CINCINATI, AND AT 04:52 HE WAS AT THE SITE OF ACCIDENT. JEFF MILLER REPORTED SEEING A DEER RUNNING ACROSS THE ROAD AND HE CUT THE WHEEL SLIGHTLY TO MISS FROM HITTING IT. THE ROAD HE WAS TRAVELING ON DID NOT HAVE ANY SHOULDER AND ONCE HE CUT THE WHEEL THE TRUCK INSTANTLY WENT OFF THE ROAD AND HE COULD NOT RECOVER. THE TRUCK WENT OUT OF CONTROL AND EVENTUALLY ROLLED OVER. ONCE THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER JEFF REALIZED HE WAS PINNED DOWN BY THE CAB OF THE TRUCK BEING CRUSHED AROUND HIM. HE REPORTED SMELL THE SMOKE AND HEARING THE FIRE START ALMOST INSTANTLY. AFTER A FEW SECONDS HE HEARD THE FIRST EXPLOSION OF THE FIRST COMPARTMENT. AT THIS TIME HE STARTED HONKING THE HORN AND YELLING FOR SOMEONE TO HELP HIM. AT THIS TIME HE WAS CRYING AND YELLING GOD PLEASE JUST LET ME SEE MY GIRLS ONE MORE TIME. THEN HE HEARD THE SECOND AND THIRD EXPLOSIONS. AT THIS TIMEHE STATED HE THOUGHT HE WASNT GOING TO MAKE IT OUT OF THIS ALIVE. HE CONTINUED TO HONK THE HORN AND YELLING FOR HELP AND AT THIS TIME HE HEARD A MAN'S VOICE TELLING HIM TO HANG IN THERE THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON ITS WAY. JEFF REPORT HIRING THE SIRENS ABOUT 30 SECONDS LATER. AFTER THE FIREMAN ARRIVED THEY CUT HIM OUT OF THE TRUCK WITHIN MINUTES.  EVERYTHING AFTER THIS POINT EVERYONE KNOWS ABOUT.  THIS IS THE ACCIDENT REPORT COMING FROM JEFF MILLER 1 HOUR AFTER BEING RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL THE SAME DAY 20TH OCTOBER 2019

column168: Driver was unloading fuel from a tanker into an underground storage container.  While the fuel was being pumped into the underground storage tank either due to driver error or pump failure there was 700 gallons of Diesel fuel spilled onto the surface.  The surface was an asphalt parking lot and the fuel followed the surface drainage and pooled in the depressions in the parking lot.  Local First responders covered the spilled area with sand to contain the spill and control the vapors. Lincoln environmental Services was called to the scene to effect the cleanup.  They swept up the contaminated sand from the concrete surface around the fuel island.  Additional absorbent was placed on any remaining fuel stains.  A skid loader was used to scrape the sand into piles.  It was then loaded into dump trucks and taken to the Box Elder Landfill in Tremonton, UT for disposal.  No drains or waterways were affected.

While offloading a truck, a Veolia employee discovered a small leak of approximately 3 gallons of waste  flammable liquid material on the floor of the trailer. Upon further investigation, the leaking 55 gallon drum was identified and overpacked into an 85 gallon drum. The leak appeared to be a result of the  55 gallon drum being over pressurized.

THE TRACTOR PULLING THE CHISEL PLOW AND NH3 TANK WAS TRAVELING DOWN THE ROAD HIT A FROST BOIL IN THE ROAD CAUSING THE TANK TO OVERTURN. WHEN THE TANK OVERTURNED IT CAUSED THE HOSE TO TEAR OFF THE VALVE. UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE ACCIDENT THE STATE MDA WAS NOTIFIED WAS WELL AS THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. WE HAD A CRANE COMPANY COME AND PICK THE TANK UP AND SET IT BACK ON ITS WHEELS FOR US. THE TOTAL TIME FOR THE INCIDENT WAS APPROXIMATELY 3.5 HOURS. THE TANK IS CURRENTLY BEING INSPECTED TO DETERMINE IF IT CAN BE PUT BACK INTO USE OR NOT. IT HAS PAINT RUBBED OFF ON THE LEFT SIDE AND IT WILL NEED THE CAGE OVER THE VALVES REPLACED.
column169: THE ONLY THING WE COULD DO TO HELP PREVENT RECURRENCE WOULD BE TO TAKE EXTRA PRECAUTIONS AND SLOW DOWN MORE YET ON POORLY MAINTAINED ROADWAYS.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column169: RETRAIN THE OPERATOR ON PROPER FORKLIFT PROCEDURES.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: A PAVING STRAIGHT TRUCK DISTRIBUTOR (CAPACITY 2000 GALLONS) WAS WESTBOUND ON US22 IN HARRISON COUNTY, OHIO, WHEN THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED A LEFT TURN ONTO CR13 IN GREEN TOWNSHIP. DUE TO HIS SPEED, HE WAS UNABLE TO COMPLETE THE TURN AND OVERTURNED 270 DEGREES IN A BARREL ROLL. HE THEN CAME TO REST OFF OF THE ROADWAY ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE VEHICLE. THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE VEHICLE FACED THE CURVED GUARDRAIL THAT WAS PLACED ALONG THE SOUTHWEST CORNER OF THE INTERSECTION. THE TOP LID (APPROXIMATELY 10" IN DIAMETER) ON THE CARGO TANK UNLATCHED DUE TO AN UNKNOWN REASON, AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 1200 TO 1800 GALLONS OF MC-70 LIQUID PAVING MATERIAL ONTO THE ROADWAY OVER A PERIOD OF LESS THAN 2 HOURS. DUE TO THE SLOPE OF THE ROADWAY, THE MATERIAL DRAINED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT AND CAME TO REST IN A PRIVATE POND ON THE RESIDENCE AT 45871 UPPER CLEAR FORK ROAD; CADIZ, OHIO 43907.  CADIZ, HOPEDALE, AND TORONTO FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE; AS WELL AS HOPEDALE EMS; HARRISON COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT; THE OHIO STATE HIGHWAY PATROL; AND THE HARRISON COUNTY EMA.  ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE DEPLOYED ACROSS THE POND, AND ABSORBENT PADS AND BOOMS WERE USED ON THE ROADWAY AND BERM. VACUUM TRUCKS WERE USED TO REMOVED THE RESIDUE FROM THE WATER'S SURFACE, AND THE THE EMBANKMENT WAS REMOVED FOR TREATMENT AND/OR DISPOSAL. THE CARGO TANK ON THIS DISTRIBUTOR TRUCK IS A NON-SPECIFICATION TANK.
column169: SINCE THE TRUCK WAS SALVAGED PRIOR TO THIS FORM BEING COMPLETED, IT IS UNKNOWN IF THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL WAS DUE TO THE TANKER CAP LATCH NOT BEING SECURED; THERE WAS FAILURE TO THE LATCH ITSELF; OR DAMAGE TO THE LATCH OCCURRED DURING THE TRAFFIC CRASH.  IN THE FUTURE, ALL DISTRIBUTOR TRUCK OPERATORS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO VISUALLY CONFIRM AT THE PLACE OF LOADING THAT THE TANK CAP IS PRESENT AND PROPERLY LATCHED. DRIVERS WILL ALSO BE INSTRUCTED TO VERIFY THESE DETAILS PRIOR TO EACH TIME THIS TYPE OF VEHICLE IS OPERATED.  SINCE THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED DUE TO THE DRIVER ERROR, SAFE VEHICLE OPERATION TOPICS (SPEED, FOLLOWING TOO CLOSELY, ETC.) WILL ALSO BE DISCUSSED IN THE SPRING WITH ALL DRIVERS PRIOR TO STARTING COMPANY PROJECTS FOR THE NEXT PAVING SEASON.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver stated per the veedor root readings all the product would fit.   He stated that product began coming out of the customers vent (1 vent for 3 tanks) spilling an estimated 15 gallons. Driver stated none got into a drain, however some did get into the grass area.  He cleaned the rest up with floor dri.  Per the Customer's instructions, the Fire Dept was called to assist.
column169: Driver was retrained on proper procedures for unloading gasoline products, but there were also issues with the readings from the store.  Both Customer and carrier determined areas of improvement needed.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column58: Fusible Pressure Relief Device or Element
column168: Driver stated that as he was offloading into one tank, the other tank began spilling Unleaded. Tanks were manifolded, and as he was unloading in one tank the other tank pressured up causing product to spill out.  Some product did get into the storm drain.
column169: Driver was retrained in unloading procedures for delivering gas, but also in proper procedures for the type of tanks involved with this Customer.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: When Driver opened the valve on the trailer, the Customer's unloading line into their tank started leaking. Driver stopped the pump and called the Customer.  Customer told him to go ahead and unload while it was leaking because they could not fix it until he was done.  It took 45 minutes to unload.   Spilled onto containment pad and gravel.  Customer is handling the cleanup.
column169: This event involved the Customer's equipment be defective.   Driver was trained in how to recognize possible problem areas in equipment to prevent these types of issues in the future.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver and the Dispatchers read the ticket and the charts wrong causing a spill at the Customer's which has run into the street.  He immediately shut down, but it kept flowing.  Driver placed rags, but he  ran out of rags.  No drains in the area but product is sitting around the curb area.    The product  started spilling from a metal cap away from the unloading area.   Fire Dept was called out.   The Fire Dept put floor dry down, it did not go into any drains, and the  estimate of 15 gallons was correct.
column169: Both Driver and Dispatchers were counseled/retrained in the correct way to read charts/BOL tickets.   Driver was also retrained in the proper procedures on dropping fuel.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver arrived to the store and looked up on the QT app via the tablet in the truck and noticed that the premium would not fit, according to the QT app.  Driver called the planning center and told them what was going on, and the planning center told him that his readings on the website would allow it to fit and to go ahead and drop the  compartment.  #1 watched the drop head blow off of the tank fitting on the ground, and he shut off the internal valves.  Driver was able to clean most of the spill up, using diapers; however, he noticed  that some had reached the sewer drain.  Safety was called.  EMI was sent out.
column169: Re-Training was done both with Driver and Dispatchers on how to read the store app and to compare the information for accuracy.  Proper procedures were again looked at for unloading fuel with the Driver to ensure for better performance in the future.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver stated no alarms went off to show that he overfilled. He stated there is a box screen to watch  for the measurements.  It flashed at him, so he switched tanks and finished unloading.   When he unhooked and left there was nothing spilled.  This was a pump off, and the Driver did not know how big the tank was.  Fuel continued to seep out of from under the tanks in the containment area.
column169: Proper unloading procedures for this facility were retrained with the Driver, but there was some question  as to whether the entire spill was GTI's.  The subcontractors met with the Customer to discuss any  issues they found.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
